1
00:00:04,750 --> 00:00:17,650
SPK_0: We have begun with a diagnosis of this problem of Gnosticism and the fact of its presence and the fact of its invisibility.

2
00:00:19,130 --> 00:00:28,270
SPK_0: And now we've begun the part of teasing it apart with the first horseman of the apocalypse, reason and the way that reason operates.

3
00:00:28,270 --> 00:00:31,630
SPK_0: In some sense, a little bit of a sense of, okay, what do we mean by reason?

4
00:00:32,270 --> 00:00:34,610
SPK_0: And how does reason go awry?

5
00:00:35,290 --> 00:00:38,710
SPK_0: We don't want to attach everything.

6
00:00:38,890 --> 00:00:40,610
SPK_0: We don't want to lay it all at the foot of reason.

7
00:00:40,650 --> 00:00:43,810
SPK_0: Reason playing its role improperly is very closely tied.

8
00:00:44,590 --> 00:00:49,470
SPK_0: And if you're paying attention, you saw at least four or five other threads begin to come up.

9
00:00:50,830 --> 00:00:53,530
SPK_0: So now we're beginning to really get into the heart of the matter.

10
00:00:53,670 --> 00:00:58,250
SPK_0: We're starting to really get into the space where there's enough between us.

11
00:00:58,270 --> 00:01:02,890
SPK_0: That hopefully we can actually really, really begin to grasp the problem we're dealing with.

12
00:01:03,090 --> 00:01:07,230
SPK_1: Yeah, so Guilty, even in the previous episode, slipped up several times.

13
00:01:07,310 --> 00:01:13,990
SPK_1: Really wanted to go into this particular direction, what becomes with reason in a Gnostic way, if it follows a Gnostic way.

14
00:01:15,070 --> 00:01:21,950
SPK_1: And what becomes with reason is that knowledge becomes power or becomes equivocated with power.

15
00:01:22,070 --> 00:01:24,350
SPK_1: And power becomes equivocated with knowledge.

16
00:01:24,570 --> 00:01:27,850
SPK_1: There is all this interesting relationship starting playing out.

17
00:01:28,270 --> 00:01:38,310
SPK_1: And to start telling the story of knowledge as a power, which, just in case, is the foundational slogan of our civilization, literally, knowledge is power.

18
00:01:38,610 --> 00:01:47,810
SPK_1: Like, that's how modernity literally started, it's a famous writing of Bacon, like, so it's not an interpretation, taking something from the ground and lifting it in a spotlight.

19
00:01:48,090 --> 00:01:53,950
SPK_1: But this story starts way before Bacon, like, in a way it starts in a garden, but it also starts in a desert.

20
00:01:54,170 --> 00:01:58,170
SPK_1: We won't go into the garden yet, at least I'm not ready to go into the garden.

21
00:01:58,270 --> 00:02:03,830
SPK_1: But I can remember desert, partially because I spent quite a lot of time in the last years in a desert, so it feels very close.

22
00:02:04,190 --> 00:02:08,270
SPK_1: But it starts in the desert in Palestine, where Jesus is tempted by a devil.

23
00:02:08,650 --> 00:02:20,930
SPK_1: And it starts with this first very practical and very particular temptation, which, truth be told, we as a secular people rarely give us even time to notice what is so...

24
00:02:21,490 --> 00:02:23,530
SPK_1: Like, we don't go into the depths of this temptation.

25
00:02:23,570 --> 00:02:28,150
SPK_1: Just a reminder, Jesus is fasting for 40 days, hungry, like, literally.

26
00:02:28,270 --> 00:02:29,830
SPK_1: Like, that's kind of what is mentioned.

27
00:02:29,950 --> 00:02:34,090
SPK_1: So, the desire arose into him, certain desires, and that's as the moment of temptation.

28
00:02:34,690 --> 00:02:35,650
SPK_1: There are three temptations.

29
00:02:35,990 --> 00:02:37,150
SPK_1: We start with the first.

30
00:02:37,450 --> 00:02:39,970
SPK_1: And the first temptation is to turn stones into bread.

31
00:02:40,390 --> 00:02:41,730
SPK_1: So, what it has to do with us?

32
00:02:41,850 --> 00:02:43,590
SPK_1: Because the guy is hungry, make stones into bread.

33
00:02:44,210 --> 00:02:44,930
SPK_1: Let's stop aside.

34
00:02:45,130 --> 00:02:45,710
SPK_1: What is it?

35
00:02:45,970 --> 00:02:50,370
SPK_1: Like, ultimately, like, on its surface level, the moment I pronounce, it's power over matter.

36
00:02:51,210 --> 00:02:53,270
SPK_1: Like, any material form of power.

37
00:02:53,790 --> 00:02:56,050
SPK_1: Like, it doesn't matter if it's a splitting atom.

38
00:02:56,430 --> 00:02:58,130
SPK_1: Whether it's, I don't know, running.

39
00:02:58,130 --> 00:03:02,030
SPK_1: running a 300,000-mile plane or whatever it is, space travels.

40
00:03:02,230 --> 00:03:04,110
SPK_1: It's all about turning stones into bread.

41
00:03:04,490 --> 00:03:09,590
SPK_1: It's a power to transcend material limitations of phenomenons.

42
00:03:10,030 --> 00:03:12,510
SPK_1: Alchemical principle to turn lead into gold.

43
00:03:13,430 --> 00:03:17,470
SPK_1: But that's the premise of the whole, if in effect, reason.

44
00:03:17,770 --> 00:03:20,230
SPK_1: Like, you're still here not exactly on knowledge yet.

45
00:03:20,370 --> 00:03:23,910
SPK_1: You still can even say that that's what, in a way, reason is trying to achieve,

46
00:03:24,030 --> 00:03:26,750
SPK_1: to go beyond the limits, like to go through the limitations,

47
00:03:26,750 --> 00:03:31,270
SPK_1: to feed the hungry, to turn stones into breads.

48
00:03:31,810 --> 00:03:34,450
SPK_1: But it's not just what is happening.

49
00:03:34,810 --> 00:03:36,370
SPK_1: This story is not alone in what is happening.

50
00:03:36,590 --> 00:03:38,050
SPK_1: Why I brought the word power?

51
00:03:38,610 --> 00:03:45,790
SPK_1: Because in the moment when you imagine that you have a knowledge achieved by reason

52
00:03:45,790 --> 00:03:50,670
SPK_1: to turn stones into bread, it immediately creates a new power relationship.

53
00:03:51,750 --> 00:03:55,070
SPK_1: The one who can feed, the one who can do it,

54
00:03:55,090 --> 00:03:56,230
SPK_1: the one who cannot.

55
00:03:56,750 --> 00:04:03,710
SPK_1: And that story tells us a very interesting part of the still-reason part,

56
00:04:03,910 --> 00:04:05,090
SPK_1: which we often overlook.

57
00:04:05,570 --> 00:04:07,390
SPK_1: There is no such thing as neutral reason.

58
00:04:07,630 --> 00:04:11,010
SPK_1: Any reason is necessarily welded by whom.

59
00:04:11,210 --> 00:04:15,250
SPK_1: And in an act of welding this reason, it becomes power.

60
00:04:15,510 --> 00:04:18,810
SPK_1: And that's why knowledge necessarily becomes power.

61
00:04:19,880 --> 00:04:20,570
SPK_0: Very nice.

62
00:04:20,910 --> 00:04:25,890
SPK_0: I mean, Machiavelli very specifically plays with the tension.

63
00:04:26,750 --> 00:04:28,390
SPK_0: And when he advises the prince and he says,

64
00:04:28,430 --> 00:04:29,970
SPK_0: look, you're trapped.

65
00:04:30,590 --> 00:04:34,530
SPK_0: On the one hand, you don't want to change anything.

66
00:04:35,130 --> 00:04:40,710
SPK_0: Because any disequilibrium in your territory leads to some instability

67
00:04:41,250 --> 00:04:44,230
SPK_0: that can overthrow what you're doing.

68
00:04:45,310 --> 00:04:48,550
SPK_0: And yet, you're surrounded by other princes.

69
00:04:49,350 --> 00:04:52,610
SPK_0: And any one of those princes who chooses to take a bite from the apple

70
00:04:52,610 --> 00:04:56,730
SPK_0: has a chance of getting power, an asymmetric advantage,

71
00:04:56,750 --> 00:04:58,530
SPK_0: and you're his lunch.

72
00:04:58,870 --> 00:05:01,330
SPK_0: So you and the other princes are playing the game,

73
00:05:01,510 --> 00:05:02,490
SPK_0: the dark forest game.

74
00:05:03,450 --> 00:05:04,430
SPK_0: So we see this, right?

75
00:05:04,470 --> 00:05:05,090
SPK_0: We see this trap.

76
00:05:05,210 --> 00:05:05,930
SPK_0: That's step two.

77
00:05:07,050 --> 00:05:08,110
SPK_1: Effectively, there's a step two.

78
00:05:08,110 --> 00:05:08,690
SPK_0: There's a step two.

79
00:05:09,790 --> 00:05:12,110
SPK_0: So first, I suppose what I'll do is I will confess

80
00:05:12,710 --> 00:05:15,190
SPK_0: and ground this in very experiential.

81
00:05:15,730 --> 00:05:18,690
SPK_0: Some number of years ago, 10, 15, I can't remember.

82
00:05:19,490 --> 00:05:22,050
SPK_0: I was having a conversation with my friend, Eric Weinstein.

83
00:05:23,110 --> 00:05:24,490
SPK_0: He was in New York at the time.

84
00:05:24,870 --> 00:05:26,190
SPK_0: And he was very frustrated.

85
00:05:26,750 --> 00:05:31,890
SPK_0: With the fact that he could not get anyone to really attend to his physics.

86
00:05:32,530 --> 00:05:35,930
SPK_0: He had a physics theory or even a meta-theory

87
00:05:35,930 --> 00:05:38,150
SPK_0: that implied across different domains like economics.

88
00:05:39,010 --> 00:05:40,310
SPK_0: And he was very frustrated.

89
00:05:40,790 --> 00:05:44,110
SPK_0: And so I counseled him in my Gnostic wisdom.

90
00:05:44,870 --> 00:05:47,290
SPK_0: I said, you're going about this all wrong.

